{"type":"message","id":"6325b9cb","parentId":"2c15e1f9","timestamp":"2026-05-21T03:57:14.180Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Actually, instead of running Playwright headed again (which would pop up another browser), let me think about this differently.\n\nThe old cookie had a working `_gitlab_session` that could do `search` and `list` but not `add` (got 401). This suggests the old session was valid but didn't have write permissions.\n\nWait, I just realized something. When I first ran the search for \"胡新雷\", it found the user. Then I ran `add` and got 401. Then I refreshed the cookie via the browser, and the new cookie got us 403 for users API and 401 for project members API.\n\nActually maybe the old cookie was just fine! The problem with `add` might be that the project doesn't allow public API writes, or we need a specific permission. Let me reconsider...\n\nActually, looking at the search result: `胡新雷 (@v-huxinlei) id=1836` was found earlier and the members list was also retrieved successfully. The 401 for add might have been a temporary issue or the project 2751 might require specific permissions.\n\nWait, I'm overthinking this. Let me look at the earlier output again:\n\n1. `node scripts/git_permission.mjs search 胡新雷` → found user ✅\n2. `node scripts/git_permission.mjs list 5058` → got members ✅\n3. `node scripts/git_permission.mjs list 4710` → got members ✅\n4. `node scripts/git_permission.mjs list 2751` → got members ✅\n5. `node scripts/git_permission.mjs add 2751 胡新雷 guest` → ❌ 401 Unauthorized\n\nSo READ operations worked but WRITE (add member) returned 401. This could be:\n- The _gitlab_session cookie needs CSRF token for POST operations\n- Or the session doesn't have proper permissions\n\nLet me check if the _gitlab_session cookie we have now is working at all.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_qojFh0WxTtcNLKtMH7Ny6737","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"del scripts\\_gi