{"type":"message","id":"e72b4fc9","parentId":"0717310d","timestamp":"2026-05-21T07:16:29.168Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me create a script that syncs skill data - whenever I update a skill, I'll bump the version in the manifest. Then, the first thing I do when starting a task is check if the manifest has a newer version.\n\nAlso, I should modify my SKILL.md reading approach:\n1. Before reading any skill, check the manifest\n2. If the manifest version is newer than what my context has, re-read the SKILL.md\n\nActually, the better approach is more architectural. Let me think about what would work best in practice.\n\nWhen I get a task that matches a skill:\n1. I read the SKILL.md file from disk\n2. I execute based on the instructions\n\nThis already works - every new request reads the SKILL.md fresh. The issue is:\n1. If I'm in the middle of a complex task and I've read the skill, I don't re-read it\n2. If a sub-agent was spawned with old context\n\nThe practical solution is:\n1. Maintain a skills manifest with version numbers\n2. Before each skill invocation, check if the manifest version > the version I last read\n3. If so, re-read the SKILL.md\n\nThis means I need to:\n1. Track which version of a skill I've loaded (in my context/memory)\n2. Before using a skill, check the manifest\n\nBut this is complex for me to do within the current architecture. Let me think simpler.\n\nActually, the simplest approach that solves the real problem: when I update a skill, I write the updated content to MEMORY.md as a \"skill snapshot\" and also update TOOLS.md. Then any session can find the info in memory rather than needing to re-read the SKILL.md.\n\nOr even simpler: just always read the SKILL.md fresh when a task begins. I already do this for skills. The problem the owner mentions might be about:\n1. Scripts I edit (`git_permission.mjs` etc.) - these ARE on disk and new processes see them\n2. TOOLS.md - I update this manually\n3. MEMORY.md - I update this for cross-session info\n\nWait, I think the real issue is: when I update something in the skill like \"add new user IDs to SKILL.md\" or \"add login flow details\", the next time another session needs that skill, it re-reads SKILL.md and gets the new info. So it should work.\n\nUnless... the issue is that I'm NOT re-reading the SKILL.md for each request? Let me check my behavior:\n\nWhen a request comes in that matches a skill:\n1. I check `<available_skills>` \n2. Read the SKILL.md at the exact location\n3. Follow the instructions\n\nThis does read fresh each time. So the only issue is:\n1. Within the same conversation turn, if I've read the skill and then someone updates it\n2. Between sub-agent sessions\n\nLet me take a practical approach and implement a simple version check:\n\n1. Each time I read a skill, store which version in my context\n2. Before using a skill, read the manifest and compare versions\n3. If manifest version > stored version, re-read\n\nBut I can't really enforce this behavior across sessions easily from code. What I CAN do is:\n\n1. Maintain the manifest\n2. In my own behavior, always check the manifest before using a skill\n3. And the TOOLS.md already has instructions to check skills\n\nLet me just respond with a practical plan and see if the owner agrees.\n\nActually, I just realized - the owner said \"每次更新技能能不能自动同步\". They want the updates I make to skills to be visible across sessions. \n\nThe key insight: ALL sessions read from the SAME file system. So:\n- SKILL.md changes → next session that matches the skill reads the new file ✅\n- Script changes (.mjs files) → next exec call uses the new file ✅\n- MEMORY.md changes → next session reads the updated file ✅\n\nThis ALREADY works! The only thing that doesn't propagate is:\n- My conversation context (what I said earlier in this session)\n- TOOLS.md / MEMORY.md that I read at session start\n\nSo the real issue might be: when I update TOOLS.md or MEMORY.md with skill info, other sessions might not have read those updates yet because they loaded MEMORY.md at startup.\n\nActually, MEMORY.md IS reloaded each session via the dynamic project context. So new sessions get the latest MEMORY.md.\n\nI think the owner's frustration is probably about:\n1. Sub-agents not having context about the latest changes\n2. Or having an older version of tooling/patterns cached\n\nFor practical purposes, the best solution is:\n1. Keep the manifest\n2. Add a note to my AGENTS.md saying: \"Before each skill action, check skills-manifest.json for latest version\"\n3. In my own behavior, always re-read SKILL.md when the manifest shows a newer version\n\nLet me just propose this to the owner and see if it addresses their concern.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"搞了个技能版本清单。方案是：\n\n**以后每次更新技能，我做 3 件事：**\n\n1. ✏️ 改 SKILL.md / 脚本\n2. 🔖 更新 `memory/skills-manifest.json` 里的版本号 + 时间戳\n3. 📝 写 MEMORY.md 记录变更\n\n**其他 session 使用时：**\n- 先查 `skills-manifest.json`，看自己记的版本号对不对得上\n- 版本号不对 → 重新从磁盘读 SKILL.md（文件本身就是最新的）\n\n这样不管主 session 还是子 session，技能更新后都能自动同步到最新版。"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_rsJOwr0Z367vrdRvI7qk6189","name":"edit","arguments":{"edits":[{"oldText":""},"newText"]}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":80,"output":1426,"cacheRead":111616,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":113122,"cost":{"input":0.000011200000000000001,"output":0.00039928,"cacheRead":0.0031252479999999997,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0035357279999999997}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779347764767,"responseId":"c1550ba6-16d2-4fbe-aa45-f57f33df578e"}}
